# Agent Discipline (multi-step, long-running work)

Complement to `@rules/core/general.mdc` and `@rules/core/anti-patterns.mdc`.
These rules target the failure modes that show up in long-running, multi-step
agent work, not in single-shot code generation.

## Goal-Driven Execution

- State explicit success criteria before starting non-trivial work.
- Loop on those criteria until verified; do not declare done from intent alone.
- Strong success criteria are what make autonomous looping safe.
- "I think this fixes it" is not a verification — running the check is.

## Surface Conflicts, Don't Average Them

- If two existing patterns in the codebase contradict, pick one (more recent /
  more tested), explain why, and flag the other for cleanup.
- Never blend conflicting patterns. The blended version is the worst option:
  twice the surface area, none of the consistency.

## Step / Token Budgets

- Long debugging loops drift; the model gradually loses track of what it has
  already tried and starts re-suggesting rejected fixes.
- If a task is sprawling past its natural scope, stop, summarize what is
  verified, and start a fresh pass.
- Pushing through a degraded context is worse than restating.

## Checkpoint Multi-Step Tasks

- After each significant step, restate three things:
  - what was done
  - what is verified
  - what remains
- Do not continue from a state you cannot describe back. If lost, stop and
  restate, do not guess forward.
- A wrong step at index 4 of a 6-step task silently corrupts steps 5 and 6.

## Fail Loud, Not Silent

- "Completed" / "tests pass" / "migration successful" are wrong if anything
  was skipped, suppressed, or unverified.
- Skipped records, suppressed errors, untested edge cases must be reported,
  not hidden in success language.
- Prefer an honest "I did X but did not verify Y" over a confident lie.
- Default to surfacing uncertainty.
